Letters: Halloween fireworks, Canada Post, poppy volunteers, Jamie Oliver, cooking classes, B.C. Place, time change, wall on US border It’s time to ban noisy Halloween fireworks, reader argues
I called 911 Sunday at about 3 a.m. after having endured hours of fireworks — rockets loud as cannons, screeching and sizzling ones and strings of firecrackers going off.
This had been happening to a lesser degree for several nights before. My large dog was constantly alarmed, barking, and running from my front window facing Hastings Street to my back door and windows facing the alley and Pender Street. He was clearly tormented and panting, and I was very worried about him.
The woman officer on 911 told me if I was worried about the dog I should take him to a vet but that it was not against the law to use fireworks on Halloween night.
With all the fire damage, injuries, disturbance and torment, isn’t it time to ban fireworks?
Gloria Kieler, Vancouver

Privatization is bad idea
Re: Michael Smyth column on mail.
Re-elected MP Lisa Raitt said, “The numbers of letters being mailed every year has fallen off a cliff.” The reality is that Canada Post in its last fiscal period showed a net profit of $198 million. This was in concert with a total economic revenue of nearly $8 billion.
Once again, the past Conservative government downplays the very successful Crown corporation in favour of privatization. Not only would we lose a profitable Crown corporation, thousands of letter carriers will lose their jobs and an aging population will need to collect its mail at unsecured letter boxes that are a haven for mail and identity thieves.
We’d also be killing another great Canadian institution and chipping away our sovereignty toward total corporate rule.
Art Green, Hope

Not here to watch your stuff
It is that time a year again where you seen poppy fund volunteers like myself at stores, selling poppies for donations to raise money for our military veterans and low-income seniors. Poppy volunteers aren’t there to watch your pets or stuff, which has happened to me.
I believe I am speaking for a lot of other volunteers when I say that we do not want to watch your things.
Andre Mollon, Langford

Cooking classes are great
English celebrity chef Jamie Oliver is bang on about kids learning to cook at school.
I was fortunate to take cooking classes in high school and therefore know how to cook all of my own food.
I’m amazed how many people know so little about how to cook and nutrition.
Teresa Mireault, Vancouver

B.C. Place still not renamed
It’s been approximately two years since we last heard anything about awarding the naming rights for B.C. Place stadium.
As the B.C. Lions and the Vancouver Whitecaps are heading into the playoffs, I can’t believe the naming rights haven’t been awarded. What’s the holdup?
Did the emails on this issue get triple deleted along with all the other B.C. Liberal emails?
Edward Rogers, Coquitlam

Let’s fall forward instead
I don’t like having to change my clocks by “falling back.” Let’s abolish the outdated practice.
But if we must change, lets “fall forward’” — put the clocks ahead an hour. Think of the things we could do if we had that extra daylight at the end of the day — go skiing, play soccer, walk in the park.
We already drive to work in the dark. Why not drive home with some light to help us see better and probably reduce the number of accidents.
Gord Gibson, Castlegar

Keep out the Yanks
If the U.S wants to put up a wall along the border between Vermont and Quebec, I’m all in favour of that great idea.
It will keep the Americans out.
Brian Barnes Steveston

‘Heatwave Hook-Ups’ Are To Summer As ‘Blizzard Buddies’ Were To Winter And Both Are Genius Shutterstock
This past winter, blizzard buddies became all the rage in major cities were it just wouldn’t stop fucking snowing. The concept was simple — find a stranger of the opposite sex to shack up with while waiting for all the snow to fucking melt.
Well now that the weather has turned from frigid to frigging humid as hell, blizzard buddies have become heatwave hook-ups as horny young people search for new friend with better air conditioning.
Some of the city’s hound dogs in heat are panting ­after women in a bid to get into the gals’ air-conditioned apartments.
As the mercury soared last week, guys started placing personal ads on Craigslist seeking escape from their sauna-like man caves.
“My air conditioner is broken and it’s too hot in my space,” wrote a 44-year-old man in Brooklyn Heights. “Would love to use it as an excuse to get out and meet someone with the potential for heavy flirtation.”
Describing himself as brown-haired, blue-eyed and “shockingly normal,” he continued: “Would love to meet someone who is looking for the same, and is not afraid of meeting quickly . . . as I can’t bear it in here any longer.”
I’m sure that guy’s A/C was working just fine but can you blame a bro for trying this approach. Personally, I think the opposite approach would score more women. Brag about the size of your HVAC and the women will come running. Probably not too fast though, it’s too fucking hot out to move too fast. 
[via NY Post]

My FIT Program: 
~
I LOVE a hard training session, I love the challenge and love laying on the floor covered in sweat panting afterwards and barely being able to walk the next 3 days haha! Most of all I love how a hard session makes me feel.
I now also love to rest and relax. It's taken me a long time to be able to properly relax. I literally have only learnt to be able to do it these past few days. I've always had trouble switching off, my mind is constantly over thinking and over analyzing EVERYTHING!
Due to stress and becoming fatigued and not listening to my body I became unwell. I have now learnt the importance of balance in ALL areas of my life - not just with my diet. There needs to be balance, we can't just work work work and train hard ALL the time as it can sometimes be too much - especially when you're already run down. A hard weights or HIIT session can actually do you more harm than good if you have adrenal fatigue because you're already in a stressed state and putting your body under more stress won't help it. 
If you're tired by all means train, and you'll probably feel better afterwards, but if you're extremely exhausted and don't feel well then take it easy! You're better off resting or going for a walk or bike ride outdoors. 
This is a lifestyle and we live this lifestyle for longevity so we have to be careful we don't overdo it and burn ourselves out!
Train hard, but rest and relax as well. Have balance and LISTEN TO YOUR BODY! - Your body will tell you something is wrong so don't ignore it like I did! 
X Em.

My Emily Skye Daily Workouts App Launch!

~

Who trains with kettle bells?

I am absolutely loving using kettle bells at the moment. You can work your whole body with them! I have a couple of kettlebells at home and I use them when I can’t get to the gym and they have me sweating and panting! I’ve been posting some workout videos using them as well - have a look through my page! :)

Fitness • Inspiration • Transformation: 
~
Our bodies are capable of so much more than we think they are, it's our mind that usually holds us back. If you're able to push past the limits your mind tries to put on you you'll be able to achieve so much more physically. 
Next time you feel like giving up ask yourself if you just feel uncomfortable and that's why you want to stop or you don't "believe" you can go on... Of course exercise is uncomfortable, of course it's going to hurt, and it's going to have you a sweaty, panting mess by the end of it. But once you accomplish it, you'll feel incredible and with consistency your quality of life will improve. Once you start feeling these benefits there will be no stopping you, it becomes addictive - but it's a healthy addiction providing you're balanced and get enough rest of course. Remember that the hardest part is convincing your mind you can do it. Don't just start something then give up, push yourself to your limits. 
Training isn't always about smashing yourself, but if you want the best results you're going to have to push yourself out of your comfort zone and challenge yourself. If you don’t, your body will have no need to change so it can try to adapt to the work load and you won't get the results you're after. 
I challenge you to challenge yourself next workout! - Get out of your comfort zone and push yourself to your limits! Get uncomfortable to become comfortable and confident with yourself. Most importantly, get uncomfortable so you can be healthy and fit and become your absolute best! :)

Como ter um cabelo Pantene Sempre que se ouve a expressão "cabelo Pantene" acho que toda a gente pensa, de imediato, num cabelão à Sara Sampaio, à Rita Pereira ou à Chiara Ferragni: ... vigor, a professora perguntou-me o que é que eu estava a fazer e eu respondi "então, isto é um cabelo Pantene". A turma achou muita graça, a professora nem tanto assim. Mas pronto, a Pantene conseguiu esta coisa fantástica que foi associar a sua marca a um cabelo de sonho, o cabelo que adoraríamos ter ... partido. A minha rotina de cuidados com o cabelo é muito simples: estou a usar o champô e o condicionador Pantene da linha Repara & Protege, uma linha que promete minimizar os estragos do calor do calor e dos tratamentos químicos, ... vai acompanhar-me o Verão todo. Para além disso, recentemente comecei a usar as Ampolas de Reparação 1 Minuto, também da Pantene, um tratamento intensivo para combater os sinais das agressões. É só aplicar no cabelo todo uma vez por semana, durante ... está. Mais simples era impossível.Se querem mais dicas sobre cuidados, penteados ou produtos, não deixem de espreitar o blog da Pantene. É lá que podem encontrar dicas das embaixadoras e dos hairstylists da marca, tendências, looks, penteados passo-a-passo e muito mais. E é também lá que se podem candidatar a ser o próximo Cabelo Pantene. Se acham que têm um cabelo maravilhoso e uma atitude a condizer, só têm de participar aqui.#publicidade

1. Post a photo of you recreating one of my posts about #HairAsthma
